==================================================
POST-MVP EXPANSION LAYER
OPERATIONAL CRITICALITY, TRUST & INCUMBENT RISK ENGINE
==================================================

PURPOSE:
The platform must understand that not all government contracts carry the same operational risk, trust requirements, or incumbent resistance.

Some contracts are:
- replaceable procurement
- commodity fulfillment
- low-risk acquisitions

Other contracts are:
- mission-critical infrastructure
- financial systems
- public safety systems
- identity systems
- secure operational systems
- benefits verification systems

The platform must distinguish between these categories because they dramatically affect:
- win probability
- operational maturity requirements
- incumbent advantage
- switching risk
- subcontracting feasibility
- execution risk

==================================================
CORE PHILOSOPHY
==================================================

The platform should NOT evaluate contracts solely by:
- technical fit
- pricing
- capability overlap

The platform MUST also evaluate:
- operational trust level
- switching cost
- incumbent entrenchment
- mission criticality
- public impact risk
- compliance burden
- operational continuity risk

==================================================
IMPORTANT SYSTEM RULE
==================================================

The more operationally critical the system:
- the stronger incumbent advantage becomes
- the more operational maturity matters
- the more trust history matters
- the less likely new vendors are to win as prime

==================================================
OPERATIONAL CRITICALITY ENGINE
==================================================

PURPOSE:
Classify contracts by operational sensitivity and trust requirements.

==================================================
CRITICALITY LEVELS
==================================================

LEVEL 1 — LOW CRITICALITY
Examples:
- office supplies
- printers
- commodity hardware
- furniture
- simple fulfillment

Characteristics:
- low switching cost
- low operational impact
- low trust sensitivity

==================================================
LEVEL 2 — MODERATE CRITICALITY
Examples:
- internal dashboards
- reporting tools
- analytics systems
- training systems
- visualization systems

Characteristics:
- moderate operational importance
- moderate switching risk

==================================================
LEVEL 3 — HIGH CRITICALITY
Examples:
- operational support systems
- secure communications
- logistics coordination
- infrastructure monitoring
- healthcare support systems

Characteristics:
- elevated trust requirements
- higher continuity requirements

==================================================
LEVEL 4 — MISSION CRITICAL
Examples:
- benefits verification
- payment systems
- identity systems
- financial verification
- law enforcement systems
- emergency response systems

Characteristics:
- extreme operational sensitivity
- high uptime expectations
- major switching risk
- strong incumbent advantage

==================================================
LEVEL 5 — NATIONAL INFRASTRUCTURE / DEFENSE SENSITIVE
Examples:
- classified systems
- defense operational infrastructure
- intelligence systems
- national communications
- critical financial infrastructure

Characteristics:
- maximum trust sensitivity
- massive operational risk
- highly restricted procurement ecosystem

==================================================
TRUST REQUIREMENT ENGINE
==================================================

PURPOSE:
Determine how much institutional trust is required for the opportunity.

FACTORS:
- financial data access
- citizen data access
- operational continuity
- public impact
- national security relevance
- integration depth
- regulatory exposure
- uptime requirements
- secure infrastructure requirements

OUTPUT:
Trust Requirement Score
0-100

==================================================
SWITCHING COST ENGINE
==================================================

PURPOSE:
Estimate how difficult and risky it is for the government to replace the incumbent vendor.

FACTORS:
- system integrations
- nationwide deployment
- operational continuity dependency
- user retraining burden
- migration complexity
- financial impact of downtime
- institutional familiarity
- operational disruption risk

==================================================
SWITCHING COST LEVELS
==================================================

LOW
Examples:
- office products
- commodity hardware
- standard fulfillment

MEDIUM
Examples:
- dashboards
- reporting systems
- internal tools

HIGH
Examples:
- operational platforms
- integrated workflows
- regional systems

EXTREME
Examples:
- financial verification
- benefits systems
- payment systems
- identity infrastructure
- mission-critical infrastructure

==================================================
INCUMBENT LOCK ENGINE
==================================================

PURPOSE:
Determine whether the incumbent vendor likely has structural advantage.

ANALYZE:
- repeat award history
- operational criticality
- integration depth
- contract duration
- recompete frequency
- agency dependence
- switching cost
- operational trust level

OUTPUT:
Incumbent Lock Score
0-100

==================================================
INCUMBENT LOCK EXAMPLES
==================================================

LOW LOCK
Examples:
- lumber procurement
- printer procurement
- generic supplies

HIGH LOCK
Examples:
- SSA financial verification systems
- benefits processing systems
- enterprise operational infrastructure

==================================================
OPERATIONAL MATURITY REQUIREMENTS
==================================================

The platform should increase required maturity when:
- trust requirements rise
- operational continuity matters
- public impact increases
- compliance burden increases
- switching cost increases

==================================================
MATURITY FACTORS
==================================================

Analyze:
- years in business
- operational scale
- compliance maturity
- federal experience
- secure infrastructure
- support capability
- uptime capability
- incident response capability
- staffing maturity
- historical operational performance

==================================================
MISSION-CRITICAL SUPPRESSION RULES
==================================================

The platform should aggressively suppress opportunities when:

- operational criticality is high
- trust requirements are high
- switching cost is extreme
- user maturity is low
- past performance is absent
- incumbent advantage is severe

unless explicitly requested by the user.

==================================================
EXAMPLE SUPPRESSION RULE
==================================================

IF:
- operational_criticality >= 4
- user_federal_past_performance = 0
- incumbent_lock_score > 70

THEN:
- suppress opportunity by default
- recommend subcontract strategy

